I came here on a Friday for lunch. There was no wait in line and was immediately seated. We ordered some appetizers and sushi from the AYCE menu and food came out within 20 min. My main complaint is their appetizers. The takoyaki was just really oily and did not have much flavor. Would've loved to see the Bonito flakes on it! The agedashi tofu is supposed to have a thin later of crisp on the outside to not overpower the tofu flavor. But instead, there was too much batter and the tofu was overcooked on the inside. All in all, don't order their appetizers.  But the sushi, the main part of the meal, was delicious! Everything tasted fresh and I was definitely pleased and full. Highly recommend their nigiris. Those were my favorite out of everything I ordered!

While most restaurants in Medford Square were either closed today or only allowed takeout, this Japanese restaurant  was open with dine-in seating. Service was good.  However, the miso soup was not. Too watery and had no flavor at all.  The salmon teriyaki was good. But the beef teriyaki was not as flavorful as in most Asian restaurants. The only rice they carry is plain white rice. Too lumpy. The only sauce they carry is  low-sodium soy sauce. No black pepper, which doesn't raise blood pressure. They had salt, which does. No sugar substitute, only white sugar. Only hot drink was green tea. Not free. No milk for tea. The tea cups are larger than you'd find in most Asian restaurants. They do carry Coke products. The only alcohol is beer and wine. Only desserts are vanilla, green tea, and red bean ice cream. Ths vanilla ice cream is good.

Nijiya is my go-to all-you-can-eat spot for good quality sashimi and a diverse selection of rolls. Yamato II is more popular, but I've found the quality to be reliably higher at Nijiya. They provide nigiri, hand rolls, sashimi and rolls, as well as sides. There are plenty of options for sushi, including the staples (ie. spicy tuna) and specials (I enjoyed the jalapeno rolls). The tempura platter is a refreshingly large portion of shrimp, butternut squash, acorn squash, and broccoli. They serve a small selection of drinks. The staff is friendly and they provide prompt service. I was actually refreshed at how often they refilled our water, especially since I drink so much. Overall, if you're in the mood for sushi, you're not going to go wrong with Nijiya. FYI, there is no parking lot, but you can park on the street and there's usually spots open within a 3 minute walk radius.
